  --- In junit@yahoogroups.com, &quot;David&quot; &lt;achepati67@y...&gt; wrote:
  &gt; &gt;Dear Members,
  &gt; &gt;
  &gt; &gt;I whould like to test a class with a main(String[] args) method.
  Depending
  &gt; &gt;on the input argument it executes one thing or the other. The
  problem is
  &gt; &gt;that on my main(String[] args) method at the end or when it founds
  an
  &gt; error,
  &gt; &gt;the method System.exit() is invoked. So when I define jUnit test
  cases
  &gt; &gt;(methods with prefix test), jUnits only runs the first test,
  because
  &gt; some&gt;System.exit() was invoked.
  &gt; &gt;Is there any way to test such kind of situations?
  &gt; &gt;Thanks in advance,
  &gt;
  &gt; The solution propoused by Bern was:
  &gt;
  &gt; java.lang.System is final and does not implement interfaces,so
  there is no
  &gt; chance to replace ist behaviour.You may want to replace calls to
  &gt; System.exit() with calls againstan interface you define. Under test
  use an
  &gt; implementation which allowsyourtest code to chech if the exit
  method has
  &gt; been called by main() but whichdoes not exit the VM. In production
  use an
  &gt; implememtation which delegatesto System.exit().
  &gt;
  &gt; As far as I know what you mean could be implemented like this: (see
  comments
  &gt; below)
  &gt;
  &gt; package com.my.example
  &gt;
  &gt; public class Example {
  &gt;       static Finish _finish = new Example.ProductionFinish();//
  private package
  &gt; (static because it is
  &gt;
              // going to be used on main.)
  &gt;       static void setFinish(Finish value){_finish = value;}      //
  private package
  &gt;
  &gt;       static main (String[] args)
  &gt;
  &gt;             boolean goOn = true;       // because we don&#39;t exit on
  testing mode,
  &gt;                                     // we need a way for
  controling the execution flow.
  &gt;             if (someCondition) {// first checking (exceptional
  flow)
  &gt;                   goOn = finish.do(-1);
  &gt;             }
  &gt;             // ... put other checking here
  &gt;             if (goOn && otherCondition) {// main flow
  &gt;                   finish.do(0);
  &gt;             }
  &gt;       }
  &gt;
  &gt;       /* Now we define the interface Finish and its default
  implementation (as
  &gt; inner classes
  &gt;       with private-package visibility, because we have to define
  ONLY for testing
  &gt; purpose this
  &gt;       interface!)*/
  &gt;
  &gt;       interface Finish {
  &gt;             boolean do(int i);
  &gt;       }
  &gt;
  &gt;       class ProductionFinish {// its default implementation (used
  on production
  &gt; mode)
  &gt;             ProductionFinish(){} // default constructor with
  private-package
  &gt; visibility
  &gt;             boolean do(int i) {
  &gt;                   System.exit(i);
  &gt;             }
  &gt;       }
  &gt; }
  &gt;
  &gt; Now on the testing class defined on the same package:
  &gt;
  &gt; package com.my.example
  &gt;
  &gt; public class ExampleTest extends TestCase{
  &gt;       // ...
  &gt;           protected void setUp (){Example.setFinish(new
  &gt; ExampleTest.TestingFinish());}
  &gt;       }
  &gt;       class TestingFinish implements Example.Finish{
  &gt;             TestingFinish (){} // default constructor with
  private-package visibility
  &gt;             boolean do(int i) { // We have to stop on every case!
  &gt;                   return false;
  &gt;             }
  &gt;       }
  &gt; }
  &gt;
  &gt; COMMENTS:
  &gt;
  &gt; - About this suggestion and the corresponding implementation,
  because we
  &gt; need a default implementation ALWAYS (for production), then instead
  of using
  &gt; an INTERFACE, it is BETTER to just define the class Finish as
  ABSTRACT (the
  &gt; do(int i) method should be abstract)
  &gt;
  &gt; - You have to write A LOT for makeing a very simple task. I have
  implemented
  &gt; a simpler solution, just do the following steps:
  &gt;
  &gt; a) Define on the class to test (Example), the static boolean field
  _TEST as
  &gt; private-package. This field is initialized with default value: false
  &gt; (production)
  &gt;
  &gt; b) Define a STATIC PRIVATE method finish, like this:
  &gt;             private static boolean finish(int i) {
  &gt;                   if(!_TEST) {
  &gt;                         System.exit(i);
  &gt;                   }
  &gt;                   return false;
  &gt;             }
  &gt; c) On the testing class (ExampleTest), set on the setup() method,
  the field
  &gt; _TEST to true.
  &gt;
  &gt;
  &gt; Now we have:
  &gt;
  &gt; package com.my.example
  &gt;
  &gt; public class Example {
  &gt;       static boolean _TEST = false;
  &gt;
  &gt;       static main (String[] args)
  &gt;
  &gt;             boolean goOn = true;
  &gt;             if (someCondition) {// fist checking
  &gt;                   goOn = finish(-1);
  &gt;             }
  &gt;             // ... put other checking here
  &gt;             if (goOn && otherCondition) {// the last condition
  (end of the program)
  &gt;                   finish(-1);
  &gt;             }
  &gt;       }
  &gt;
  &gt;       private static boolean finish (int i) {
  &gt;             if (!_TEST) {
  &gt;                   System.exit(i);
  &gt;             }
  &gt;             return false;
  &gt;       }
  &gt; }
  &gt;
  &gt; package com.my.example
  &gt;
  &gt; public class ExampleTest extends TestCase{
  &gt;       // ...
  &gt;           protected void setUp (){Example._TEST = true;}
  &gt;       }
  &gt; }
  &gt;
  &gt; I think this solution is enough. Any suggestion?
  &gt;
  &gt; Thanks in advance,
  &gt;
  &gt; David


  Just wondering how the testMain() looks like? How do you cover for
  all different arguments combination? Do you have to separate testMain
  () for each scenario? Thanks!
  [David Leal] In general I have the following test methods:
  testMain_help for testing when the user invokes the &quot;-h&quot;. &quot;-help&quot; on my
case.
  testMain_exceptionalFlow for testing situation that produces errors and
the process is abruptly stoped.
  testMain_mainFlow it is the main flow execution.

  I coollects all possible outputs: error and standard output on files
(using the methods: System.setOut(), System.setErr()) and then compare the
files with the expected ones. That is may test.

  That is my aproach, because on test mode the main() method doesn&#39;t finish
(Example._TEST= true), we can test more than one invocation to the method.

  Hope this help,

  David



